FW: [Ext] Helix Commodities - 66774 - United States - Cresta Metallics LLC

Hi all,
We have a new enquiry from Helix Commodities
who are looking for cover on behalf of their private credit fund
Helix
Mining Credit Partners "HMP". The fund is focused on making structured credit investments in mining and
critical mineral companies, and it's 99% owned by
Helix.
The transaction in question is in relation
HMP's term loan made to
Cresta Metallics LLC, which is a fully integrated taconite iron ore mine, beneficiation plant, and pelletising facility
located in
Prague, Oklahoma. Operations are due to start in Q2'26, and ramping up to full capacity by the end of the year.
Cresta is 100% owned and controlled via the
Ossar group, who have invested over USD 1Bn of equity in the project on top of almost USD 1Bn of shareholder
loans.
The term loan is a USD 520M 5 year Senior Secured Facility, of which
HMP has funded USD 500M, and from what I understand, another USD 20M has been funded by additional
party. The loan will be repaid by an Excess Cash Flow Sweep
with an expected weighted average life of c. 3.4 years. The security package will include a) first priority
mortgage liens on the plant, fixed assets, and equipment; b) accounts, cash, and receivables; c) inventory and
mineral rights; d) contracts rights.
Further details can be found in the deal teaser attached.
We're looking for up to USD 225M of cover at 90% indemnity.
Helix are currently in the process of lining up additional lenders, and their intention is to sell down their overall
participation to USD 250M.
Helix view
Cresta as a high-quality credit with material asset coverage and strong sponsor support, in addition
Helix are also lined up as one of the main offtakers of the production. Although please note that
Helix’s offtake does not service the term loan as this is not a prepayment. Finally, it's perhaps worth noting the
current US administration's backing of domestic
critical resource production and encouraging foreign investment, so it does seem like this project fits very well
within that initiative.
I hope this is of interest, and please let me know if you have any questions.
Kind regards,
Kevin
